---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="About Matthew Takara — background, research, and the thinking behind this site."
>
  <h1>About</h1>

  <section>
    <h2>Background</h2>
    <p>
      I'm a civil and environmental engineering student at Carnegie Mellon University.
      My research sits at the intersection of environmental sensing, embedded systems, and
      data infrastructure — building systems that observe the physical world at scale.
    </p>
    <p>
      I've worked on multi-node sensing deployments using Jetson Orin Nano hardware,
      analog signal-conditioning chains for geophone arrays, and applied machine learning
      in industry. I'm comfortable moving between hardware constraints, signal processing,
      and the software layer above it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>This site</h2>
    <p>
      Most "sustainable" websites claim green credentials without publishing the numbers.
      This site is an attempt to do the opposite: measure first, claim second.
    </p>
    <p>
      It's built with Astro (static HTML, no server-side rendering per request), uses only
      system fonts (zero font download cost), serves WebP/AVIF images, and defaults to
      dark mode (lower pixel luminance on OLED screens).
      The homepage targets under 100&nbsp;kB total transfer.
    </p>
    <p>
      In a later phase, a Raspberry Pi 5 will host the site directly and a Python collector
      will measure real wattage via a smart plug, correlate with grid carbon intensity from
      the Electricity Maps API, and publish the result to a live dashboard here.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="methodology">
    <h2>Methodology</h2>
    <p>
      <em>This section will expand as the measurement layer is built out.</em>
      The full methodology — what's measured, what's estimated, and where the
      uncertainty lies — will live in <a href="/green">the /green page</a> once
      the Pi and smart plug are running.
    </p>
    <p>
      For now: page weight is measured in browser DevTools Network tab.
      Carbon estimates for Cloudflare Pages use the
      <a href="https://developers.cloudflare.com/sustainability/" rel="noopener noreferrer">
        Cloudflare sustainability documentation
      </a> as a starting point.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
